Project with Arvato: Identify Customer Segments¶

Applied unsupervised learning techniques to identify segments of the population that form the core customer base for a mail-order sales company in Germany, Arvato-Bertelsmann. These segments can then be used to direct marketing campaigns towards audiences that will have the highest expected rate of returns. The data that you will use has been provided by our partners at Bertelsmann Arvato Analytics, and represents a real-life data science task.

Step 0: Load the Data ¶

There are four files associated with this project (besides this .ipynb):

  • Udacity_AZDIAS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for the general population of Germany; 891211 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Udacity_CUSTOMERS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for customers of a mail-order company; 191652 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Data_Dictionary.md: Detailed information file about the features in the provided datasets.
  • AZDIAS_Feature_Summary.csv: Summary of feature attributes for demographics data; 85 features (rows) x 4 columns

Step 1: Preprocessing ¶

Step 1.1: Assess Missing Data¶

The feature summary file contains a summary of properties for each demographics data column. This file will help us to make cleaning decisions during this stage of the project, while assessing the demographics data in terms of missing data.

Step 1.1.1: Convert Missing Value Codes to NaNs¶

The fourth column of the feature attributes summary (loaded in above as feat_info) documents the codes from the data dictionary that indicate missing or unknown data. While the file encodes this as a list (e.g. [-1,0]), this will get read in as a string object. We'll do a little bit of parsing to make use of it to identify and clean the data.

Go back to Index

In [6]:
# Identify missing or unknown data values and convert them to NaNs.

def mapping_nan(df, mapper, mapper_column_name, mapper_column_definition, non_numerical_indicators=[]):
    # For each mapper_df row definition
    for index, row in mapper.iterrows():
        
        # Omit rows with no NaNs or with lists without values
        if len(row[mapper_column_definition]) > 0 and row[mapper_column_definition] != ['']:
            try:
                # For each column definition build a list of nan_indicators
                replace_mask = []
                for nan_indicator in row[mapper_column_definition]:
                    
                    if nan_indicator in non_numerical_indicators:
                        replace_mask.append(nan_indicator)
                    else:
                        replace_mask.append(int(nan_indicator))
                
                # Replace masked values with NaN
                df[row[mapper_column_name]] = df[row[mapper_column_name]].replace(replace_mask, np.nan)
                
            except Exception as e:
                print('Exception: {} -> {} --> {}'.format(row[mapper_column_name], str(e), nan_indicator))
                continue
                
    return df

If values are missing completely at random, the data sample is likely still representative of the population. But if the values are missing systematically, analysis may be biased. Missing completely at random (MCAR), Missing at random (MAR), Missing not at random (MNAR)" Wikipedia: Missing Data

Step 1.1.3: Assess Missing Data in Each Row¶

How much data is missing in each row? We'll divide the data into two subsets: one for data points that are above some threshold for missing values, and a second subset for points below that threshold.

In order to know what to do with the outlier rows, we should see if the distribution of data values on columns that are not missing data (or are missing very little data) are similar or different between the two groups.

Go back to Index

In [19]:
# How much data is missing in each row of the dataset?
def count_nan_row (df):
    d={'total_missing':df.isnull().sum(axis=1).sort_values(ascending=False),'%_missing':np.round((df.isnull().mean(axis=1)*100).sort_values(ascending=False),2)}
    return(pd.DataFrame(d))

# Compare the distribution of values for at least five columns where there are
# no or few missing values, between the two subsets.

def dist_threshold(cols_list, threshold, low_nan, high_nan):
    for col in cols_list:
        fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2)
        #fig.set_title('Distribution of values per row, column {}\n\n'.format(col),fontsize=20)

        ax1.title.set_text('Low count: <{} missing values per row'.format(threshold))
        sns.countplot(low_nan[col], ax=ax1)

        ax2.title.set_text('High count: >{} missing values per row'.format(threshold))
        sns.countplot(high_nan[col], ax=ax2)
    
        plt.show()

Discussion 1.1.3: Assess Missing Data in Each Row¶

  • More than 600,000 observations without missing values (after removing features considered 'outliers')
  • Columns with low count of null values have different distributions between rows with >threshold missing values per value. Especifically, a category with outstanding count (x3-x5 comparing with other category values)
  • Except column W_KEIT_KIND_HH, other chosen columns (with high count of nans) distributions for observations with >threshold and < threshold of missing values are similar.
  • Tried threshold = [15,20,25]

If the distributions of non-missing features look similar between the data with many missing values and the data with few or no missing values, then we could argue that simply dropping those points from the analysis won't present a major issue. On the other hand, if the data with many missing values looks very different from the data with few or no missing values, then we should make a note on those data as special. Looking at the overall visualizations above, I consider missing data as ¨special¨ and won´t be removed.

Step 1.2: Select and Re-Encode Features¶

Checking for missing data isn't the only way in which a dataset can be prepared for analysis. Since the unsupervised learning techniques to be used will only work on data that is encoded numerically, we'll need to make a few encoding changes or additional assumptions to be able to make progress.

Go back to Index

Summary of types of measurement.

  • For numeric and interval data, these features can be kept without changes.
  • Most of the variables in the dataset (49) are ordinal in nature. While ordinal values may technically be non-linear in spacing, we'll make the simplifying assumption that the ordinal variables can be treated as being interval in nature (that is, kept without any changes).
  • Special handling may be necessary for the remaining two variable types: categorical, and 'mixed'.

For categorical data, we need to encode the levels as dummy variables.

Discussion 1.2.1: Re-Encode Categorical Features¶

Categorical features have been explored and handled based on if they are binary or multi-level:

  • Binary (two-level) categoricals that take numeric values, kept them without doing anything.
  • There is one binary variable that takes on non-numeric values. Re-encoded the values as numbers or create a dummy variable.
  • For multi-level categoricals (three or more values), encoded values using multiple dummy variables for 3 selected variables (CST_GESAMTTYP, FINANZTYP) and dropped the rest from the analysis.

Step 1.2.2: Engineer Mixed-Type Features¶

There are a handful of features that are marked as "mixed" in the feature summary that require special treatment in order to be included in the analysis. There are two in particular that deserve attention:

  • "PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE" combines information on three dimensions: generation by decade, movement (mainstream vs. avantgarde), and nation (east vs. west). While there aren't enough levels to disentangle east from west, you should create two new variables to capture the other two dimensions: an interval-type variable for decade, and a binary variable for movement.
  • "CAMEO_INTL_2015" combines information on two axes: wealth and life stage. Break up the two-digit codes by their 'tens'-place and 'ones'-place digits into two new ordinal variables (which, for the purposes of this project, is equivalent to just treating them as their raw numeric values).

Step 1.2.3: Complete Feature Selection¶

To summarize, the dataframe should consist of the following:

  • All numeric, interval, and ordinal type columns from the original dataset.
  • Binary categorical features (all numerically-encoded).
  • Engineered features from other multi-level categorical features and mixed features.

Make sure that:

  • For any new columns that you have engineered, that you've excluded the original columns from the final dataset.
  • Data should only be from the subset with few or no missing values.

#Auxiliary cleaning functions

def drop_cols(df,mapper):
    ''' Identifies and drops features with >34% of missing values
        Input: dataframe with missing values encoded as NaN
        Output: df without columns with >34% missing values 
    ''' 
    data_nan=pd.DataFrame({'total_missing':df.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False),
                           '%_missing':np.round((df.isnull().mean()*100).sort_values(ascending=False),2)})
    features_drop=data_nan.loc[data_nan['%_missing']>34].index.tolist()
    df=df.drop(features_drop, axis=1)
    #removing columns from mapper df
    mapper=mapper.loc[~mapper.attribute.isin(features_drop)]
    return df, mapper

def drop_rows(df):
    ''' Identifies and drops rows with >15% of missing values
        Input: dataframe with missing values encoded as NaN
        Output: df without rows with >15% missing values 
    ''' 
    data_nan_row=pd.DataFrame({'total_missing':df.isnull().sum(axis=1),
                               '%_missing':np.round((df.isnull().mean(axis=1)*100),2)})
    lowna_df=df.loc[data_nan_row['%_missing']<15]
    return lowna_df

def encode_cat(df, mapper):
    ''' Identifies categorical features and re-encodes the values as numbers 
        Input: dataframe with missing values encoded as NaN
        Output: df with numerical categorical features
    ''' 
    # Assess categorical variables: which are binary, which are multi-level, and which one needs to be re-encoded?
    cat_cols=list(mapper.loc[mapper['type']=='categorical']['attribute'])
    bi_cols=[]
    bi_non_num=[]
    multi_cols=[]
    for col in cat_cols:
        if df[col].nunique()>2: #if multi_cols
            multi_cols.append(col)
        elif df[col].dtype=='object':
            bi_non_num.append(col)
        else:
            bi_cols.append(col)
    
    # re-encode non_num Binary variables as numbers 
    for bi in bi_non_num:
        df.loc[:, bi].replace({'W':0, 'O':1}, inplace=True)
    
    #Multi-level features that we will keep. Removed the rest multi level from list
    multi_sel=['CJT_GESAMTTYP','FINANZTYP']
    for sel in multi_sel:
        if sel in multi_cols:
            multi_cols.remove(sel)#, inplace=True)
    #Dropping the multilevel categorical columns not in multi_sel list    
    df.drop(multi_cols, axis=1, inplace=True)
    #Encoding categorical variables: selected multi-level variables
    df=pd.get_dummies(df, columns=multi_sel, drop_first=True )#dummy_na=True
    
    return df

def engineer_mix(df,mapper):
    ''' Identifies 'mixed' features, drops most of them and engineers 'PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE' and 'CAMEO_INTL_2015'
        Input: dataframe with missing values encoded as NaN
        Output: df with 'PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE' and 'CAMEO_INTL_2015' features deconstructed
    ''' 
    #encoding decade (40's=0,50's=1,60's=2,70's=3,80's=4,90's=5)
    if 'PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE' in df.columns:
        decade_encoding={1:0, 2:0, 3:1, 4:1, 5:2,6:2,7:2,8:3,9:3,10:4,11:4,12:4,13:4,14:5,15:5}
        df['decade']=df.loc[:, 'PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].replace(decade_encoding)
        #encoding movement (Mainstream=1, Avantgarde=0)
        mov_encoding={1:1, 2:0, 3:1, 4:0, 5:1, 6:0, 7:0, 8:1, 9:0, 10:1, 11:0, 12:1, 13:0, 14:1,15:0}
        df['movement']=df.loc[:, 'PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].replace(mov_encoding)
    
    if 'CAMEO_INTL_2015' in df.columns:
        #encoding wealth
        df['Wealth']=[int(str(row)[0]) if pd.isna(row)==False else row for row in df['CAMEO_INTL_2015']]
        #encoding life stage
        df['Life_stage']=[int(str(row)[1]) if pd.isna(row)==False else row for row in df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'] ]
        
    #mixed columns names
    mixed_cols=list(mapper.loc[mapper['type']=='mixed']['attribute'])
    df.drop(mixed_cols, axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    return df


# Identify missing or unknown data values and convert them to NaNs.
def mapping_nan(df, mapper, mapper_column_name, mapper_column_definition, non_numerical_indicators=[]):
    # For each mapper_df row definition
    for index, row in mapper.iterrows():
        
        # Omit rows with no NaNs or with lists without values
        if len(row[mapper_column_definition]) > 0 and row[mapper_column_definition] != ['']:
            try:
                # For each column definition build a list of nan_indicators
                replace_mask = []
                for nan_indicator in row[mapper_column_definition]:
                    
                    if nan_indicator in non_numerical_indicators:
                        replace_mask.append(nan_indicator)
                    else:
                        replace_mask.append(int(nan_indicator))
                
                # Replace masked values with NaN
                df[row[mapper_column_name]] = df[row[mapper_column_name]].replace(replace_mask, np.nan)
                
            except Exception as e:
                print('Exception: {} -> {} --> {}'.format(row[mapper_column_name], str(e), nan_indicator))
                continue
                
    return df

# Main cleaning function

def clean_data(df):
    """
    Perform feature trimming, re-encoding, and engineering for demographics
    data
    
    INPUT: Demographics DataFrame
    OUTPUT: Trimmed and cleaned demographics DataFrame
    """
    mapper=pd.read_csv('AZDIAS_Feature_Summary.csv', delimiter=';')
    mapper_column_name='attribute'
    mapper_column_definition= 'missing_or_unknown'
    non_numerical_indicators=['X', 'XX']
      
    # Remove brackets and split strings into lists in feat_info.missing_or_unknown
    mapper[mapper_column_definition] = mapper[mapper_column_definition].str.strip('[').str.strip(']').str.split(',')
    # convert missing value codes into NaNs, ...
    df=mapping_nan(df, mapper, mapper_column_name, mapper_column_definition, non_numerical_indicators)
    print('Missing values codes converted into NaNs',df.shape)
    # remove selected columns and rows, ...
    df,mapper=drop_cols(df,mapper)
    print('Identified and removed cols',df.shape)
    df=drop_rows(df)
    print('Identified and removed rows',df.shape)
    # select, re-encode, and engineer column values.
    df= encode_cat(df, mapper)
    print('Identified and encoded categorical variables',df.shape)
    df= engineer_mix(df, mapper)
    print('Identified and treated mixed variables',df.shape)
    
    # Return the cleaned dataframe.
    return df

Step 2: Feature Transformation¶

Step 2.1: Apply Feature Scaling¶

Before we apply dimensionality reduction techniques to the data, we need to perform feature scaling so that the principal component vectors are not influenced by the natural differences in scale for features. Keeping an eye on the API reference page for sklearn this substep checks the following:

  • sklearn requires that data not have missing values in order for its estimators to work properly. Cleaning the remaining missing values can be as simple as just removing all data points with missing data, or applying an Imputer to replace all missing values. A more complicated procedure may be to remove missing values in order to compute the scaling parameters before re-introducing those missing values and applying imputation. A discussion on how much missing data the set has and what possible effects each approach might have on the analysis, are justify below.
  • For the actual scaling function, a StandardScaler instance is suggested, scaling each feature to mean 0 and standard deviation 1.
  • For these classes, we'll make use of the .fit_transform() method to both fit a procedure to the data as well as apply the transformation to the data at the same time.

def drop_missing_rows(df):
    ''' Identifies and drops rows with missing values
        Input: dataframe with missing values encoded as NaN
        Output: df without rows with missing values 
    ''' 
    data_nan_row=pd.DataFrame({'total_missing':df.isnull().sum(axis=1),
                               '%_missing':np.round((df.isnull().mean(axis=1)*100),2)})
    lowna_df=df.loc[data_nan_row['%_missing']<1]
    #highna_df=df.loc[data_nan_row['%_missing']>15]
    return lowna_df

Discussion 2.1: Apply Feature Scaling¶

Dealing with missing values¶

  • Remove rows:
    • Pro:Easy to drop and easy to post-work.
    • Con: We will loose lots of info, including self-selection bias insights. But we still have a 'healthy' features/observations proportion.
  • Impute mean/mode/0/or very small/large/KNN
    • Mean/mode/KNN: Con: we may add noise to the info
    • Very small or very large number to differenciate nans from other values: Usually, the best method for consumer data that may convey self-selection bias. the user has chosen to not give that kind of information: by not filling out her profile, or by changing her privacy settings, or even by deleting her cookies. That’s crucial information for the predictive model that we would lose, if we were replacing or deleting the missing values as above.

Featuring Scaling Observations¶

  • Scaling each feature to mean 0 and standard deviation 1, provides an equivalent weight to each feature.

Step 2.2: Perform Dimensionality Reduction¶

Apply dimensionality reduction techniques to the scaled data.

  • Sklearn's PCA class applies principal component analysis on the data, thus finding the vectors of maximal variance in the data. To start, you should not set any parameters (so all components are computed) or set a number of components that is at least half the number of features (so there's enough features to see the general trend in variability).
  • Ratio of variance explained by each principal component as well as the cumulative variance explained: The cumulative or sequential values using matplotlib's plot() function. Based on the findings, the number of transformed features retained for the clustering part of the project is selected.

def scree_plot(pca):
    '''
    Creates a scree plot associated with the principal components 
    
    INPUT: pca - the result of instantian of PCA in scikit learn
            
    OUTPUT:
            None
    '''
    num_components=len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
    ind = np.arange(num_components)
    vals = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
 
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax = plt.subplot(111)
    cumvals = np.cumsum(vals)
    ax.bar(ind, vals)
    ax.plot(ind, cumvals)
    #for i in range(num_components):
        #ax.annotate(r"%s%%" % ((str(vals[i]*100)[:4])), (ind[i]+0.2, vals[i]), va="bottom", ha="center", fontsize=12)
 
    ax.xaxis.set_tick_params(width=0)
    ax.yaxis.set_tick_params(width=2, length=12)
 
    ax.set_xlabel("Principal Component")
    ax.set_ylabel("Variance Explained (%)")
    plt.title('Explained Variance Per Principal Component')

Discussion 2.2: Perform Dimensionality Reduction¶

  • It is possible that too many features in the dataset lead to overfitting or the curse of dimensionality. Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a feature extraction technique* that is used to reduce the dimensionality of your dataset. The reduced features are called principal components, or latent features. These principal components are simply a linear combination of the original features in the dataset and they have two major properties:

    • They aim to capture the most amount of variability in the original dataset.
    • They are orthogonal to (independent of) one another.

  • The amount of variance explained by each component is called an eigenvalue. By visualizing the combined plot of explained variance and cumulative explained variance, it's observed that the most related 30 principal components provide most of the information as the cumulative variance explained curve estabilizes by that point. Principal components are also known as eigenvectors.

*Feature Selection and Feature Extraction are two general approaches for reducing the number of features in your data. Feature Selection processes result in a subset of the most significant original features in the data, while Feature Extraction methods like PCA construct new latent features that well represent the original data.

Step 2.3: Interpret Principal Components¶

Once we've got transformed principal components, it's a nice idea to check out the weight of each variable on the first few components to see if they can be interpreted in some fashion.

Each principal component is a unit vector that points in the direction of highest variance (after accounting for the variance captured by earlier principal components). The further a weight is from zero, the more the principal component is in the direction of the corresponding feature. If two features have large weights of the same sign (both positive or both negative), then increases in one tend expect to be associated with increases in the other. To contrast, features with different signs can be expected to show a negative correlation: increases in one variable should result in a decrease in the other.

  • To investigate the features, each weight will be map to their corresponding feature name, then sort the features according to weight. The most interesting features for each principal component will be those at the beginning and end of the sorted list. Use the data dictionary document to help you understand these most prominent features, their relationships, and what a positive or negative value on the principal component might indicate.
  • Investigate and interpret feature associations from the first three principal components in this substep.

def get_kmeans_score(data, center):
    '''
    returns the kmeans score regarding SSE for points to centers
    INPUT:
        data - the dataset you want to fit kmeans to
        center - the number of centers you want (the k value)
    OUTPUT:
        score - the SSE score for the kmeans model fit to the data
    '''
    #instantiate kmeans
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=center)

    # Then fit the model to your data using the fit method
    model = kmeans.fit(data)
    
    # Obtain a score related to the model fit
    score = np.abs(model.score(data))
    
    return score

scores = []

    scores.append(get_kmeans_score(azdias_30pca, center))

Discussion 3.1: Apply Clustering to General Population¶

  • Multiple cluster counts have been tested on the general demographics data, and the average point-centroid distances have been reported. A decision on the number of clusters to use is made and justified.
  • Elbow Method: It uses SSE (a.k.a., Cluster Inertia) to evaluate the goodness of split. We create an elbow plot of SSE for K clusters ranging from 2 to 30. As K increases, the corresponding SSE will decrease. We’ll observe the trade-off between K and SSE (we want the SSE to be low while keeping K at a reasonable value). We typically pick the optimal value of K when we see SSE starts to flatten out and forms an elbow shape.
  • Chosen number of clusters to segment the population based on above plot: 11 clusters as in the plot is observed that at that point SSE starts to flatten out so more clusters provide not as much improvement as observed.

# Main cleaning function

def new_clean_data(df):
    """
    Perform feature trimming, re-encoding, and engineering for demographics
    data. Difference with basic function clean_data is that the above drop rows with >15% nans and this one removes completely these rows
    
    INPUT: Demographics DataFrame
    OUTPUT: Trimmed and cleaned demographics DataFrame
    """
    mapper=pd.read_csv('AZDIAS_Feature_Summary.csv', delimiter=';')
    mapper_column_name='attribute'
    mapper_column_definition= 'missing_or_unknown'
    non_numerical_indicators=['X', 'XX']
      
    # Remove brackets and split strings into lists in feat_info.missing_or_unknown
    mapper[mapper_column_definition] = mapper[mapper_column_definition].str.strip('[').str.strip(']').str.split(',')
    # convert missing value codes into NaNs, ...
    df=mapping_nan(df, mapper, mapper_column_name, mapper_column_definition, non_numerical_indicators)
    print('Missing values codes converted into NaNs',df.shape)
    # remove selected columns and rows, ...
    df,mapper=drop_cols(df,mapper)
    print('Identified and removed cols',df.shape)
    df=drop_missing_rows(df)
    print('Identified and removed rows',df.shape)
    # select, re-encode, and engineer column values.
    df= encode_cat(df, mapper)
    print('Identified and encoded categorical variables',df.shape)
    df= engineer_mix(df, mapper)
    print('Identified and treated mixed variables',df.shape)
    
    # Return the cleaned dataframe.
    return df

Step 3.3: Compare Customer Data to Demographics Data¶

At this point, you have clustered data based on demographics of the general population of Germany, and seen how the customer data for a mail-order sales company maps onto those demographic clusters. In this final substep, you will compare the two cluster distributions to see where the strongest customer base for the company is.

Consider the proportion of persons in each cluster for the general population, and the proportions for the customers. If we think the company's customer base to be universal, then the cluster assignment proportions should be fairly similar between the two. If there are only particular segments of the population that are interested in the company's products, then we should see a mismatch from one to the other. If there is a higher proportion of persons in a cluster for the customer data compared to the general population (e.g. 5% of persons are assigned to a cluster for the general population, but 15% of the customer data is closest to that cluster's centroid) then that suggests the people in that cluster to be a target audience for the company. On the other hand, the proportion of the data in a cluster being larger in the general population than the customer data (e.g. only 2% of customers closest to a population centroid that captures 6% of the data) suggests that group of persons to be outside of the target demographics.

Which cluster or clusters are underrepresented in the customer dataset compared to the general population, and what kinds of people are typified by these clusters?
